{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b72970cf-e6e8-4889-a064-c83810fd9a45","content":"With Microsoft.Testing.Platform on .NET 8, platform-specific options go after `--` when using `dotnet test`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage \\\n  --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n\n| VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang` | `--hangdump` |\n| `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\n**Required NuGet packages** (add to test projects):\n\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump`\n- `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump`\n\nAlso ensure your test project has:\n\n```xml\n<UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>true</UseMicrosoftTestingPlatformRunner>\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ec4da1b3-99c1-4f11-9a16-fe5b26d23390","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing tooling migration, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n1. `--filter` → `--filter` (same, but may need `--` separator)\n2. `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` (built-in)\n3. `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--collect-coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage, or use `--coverage` with the built-in coverage\n\n\n4. Blame-related flags like `--blame-crash`, `--blame-hang`, and `--blame-hang-timeout` work similarly but may require different syntax with the `--` separator\n5. When using Microsoft.Testing.Platform, `dotnet test` still acts as a wrapper, so the command structure remains familiar—I'd run something like `dotnet test --filter \"Category=Integration\" --report-trx --coverage` to get the equivalent behavior. --coverage-output-format cobertura --blame-crash --blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m\n```\n\nOr running the test executable directly with the same platform-specific arguments. The Microsoft.Testing.Platform supports several extensions through NuGet packages: TRX reporting via `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`, code coverage via `Microsoft.CodeCoverage`, and crash/hang diagnostics through `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump` and `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump` packages, each mapping to their respective command-line flags. the packages I need to reference are `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport`, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage`, `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump`, and `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump`.","outputTokens":1358,"requestId":"5C27:127F79:9BD4B:C52F5:69F54AF0"},"id":"ca6b59ea-543d-4202-9742-1292499e8762","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:53:25.736Z","parentId":"6107e7cd-3195-48bd-98be-40cf83445434"}
